{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11695"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.51,0.23,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43826"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4310"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"2181"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44871"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43826"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with an 18-month history of right eye decrease in vision. She has no other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, her visual acuity in the right eye is 6/60 and 6/6 in the left eye; two years ago she had 6/6 visual acuity in both eyes. The pupils are equal in size and 5 mm in diameter. The left is normally reactive, whilst the right is minimally reactive. There is an afferent pupillary defect in the right eye. Fundoscopy shows a whitish pale right disc with minimal blurriness of the disc margins and a hyperaemic pink/red left disc with elevation and blurry margins obscuring the blood vessels crossing the disc. No disc cupping is present in either eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to be diagnostic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["TSH, T4, T3 blood levels","Fasting blood sugar","CT head","B scan ultrasound of the right eye","Lumbar puncture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has evidence of a compressive lesion affecting her right optic nerve with a suggestion of optic atrophy (pale right optic disc) with reduced Snellen acuity and relative afferent pupillary defect. She also has evidence of disc swelling in the other eye (left eye), however, the optic nerve function in the left eye does not seem to have yet been affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanism behind the clinical picture of the optic discs appearance is related to the location and the mass effect of the presumed tumour. The tumour is in close proximity to the right optic disc, this causes a compressive neuropathy leading to the white/pale appearance of the nerve. As there are not enough nerve fibres remaining, the compression does not cause papilloedema in the right optic nerve. However, the enlarging tumour leads to papilloedema in the left eye secondary to the rise in the intracranial pressure caused by the tumour\u2019s growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis unique clinical appearance is a classical presentation of Foster Kennedy syndrome, where a space occupying lesion in close proximity to one of the optic nerves causes compressive neuropathy in one eye and papilloedema in the other eye. Examples of such tumours are frontal cortex tumors or a meningioma in the wing of the sphenoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases with suspected space-occupying tumours, neuroimaging is required with a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT head \u003C/strong\u003Eor MRI brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function test \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E blood glucose\u003C/strong\u003E level may be part of the workup if the suspected lesion was a pituitary adenoma however on their own, these investigations are unlikely to yield a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no role for \u003Cstrong\u003EB scan ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E in this case as the suspected diagnosis is not a localised intraocular/intraorbital pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E (LP) might also be part of the workup particularly if benign intracranial hypertension was suspected. However in this case it would be a fatal mistake to prefer LP over neuroimaging. Lumbar puncture in a case of suspected intracranial tumour may cause coning of the mid-brain resulting in sudden death. In addition LP in tumour cases are not necessarily diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Foster Kennedy Syndrome is caused by a space-occupying lesion that leads to optic atrophy of one optic nerve and disc swelling in the other"],"references":["Vickers A, Ponce C, Zhou Y. Foster-Kennedy vs Pseudo-Foster-Kennedy. In: EyeWiki [online]. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.aao.org/Foster-Kennedy_vs_Pseudo-Foster-Kennedy"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28823"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-28T18:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T11:16:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4310"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, eva